english:
  title: Epitaph for Kwŏn Munjeong, Duke of Yŏngga
  author: Lee Jeyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the year of Xinchǒu of the Dade era, when Kwŏn Munjeong, the Keeper of Rites, held office, I fortunately passed the civil examination. The Minister took me as his son-in-law, and thus I served him as my teacher for forty-seven years. In the year of Bingxu of the Zhizheng era, when the Minister had reached eighty-five years of age, illness came upon him in autumn. On the twenty-ninth day of the tenth month of winter, he commanded those at his side to support him upright, and sitting with perfect composure, he departed this world. I rushed to pay my respects and wept bitterly. Days later, his grieving sons approached me with tears and said: "You once composed an epitaph for our mother. Now our father too has left us, and we wish to inter him in the Pasolwŏn field of Dŏksu County on the seventeenth day of the tenth month. Who but you can give luster to this resting place of the honored dead?" Thus I withdrew and set down this account.

    The Minister was of the Kwŏn clan of Kilch'ang, his given name was Yŏng, his courtesy name was Kigyŏng. Later his name was changed to Po, with the courtesy name Jeman. His great-grandfather, whose name was Suping, served as Left Minister of Works. His grandfather, whose name was Wai, was a Hanlin Scholar. His father, whose name was Dan, retired as Counsel to the Throne with the posthumous name Master Munching. His mother was of the No clan, daughter of the Court Remonstrator Yon.

    At fifteen, the Minister was selected for the civil service examination and passed in the year of Gimyo. He took first place in the palace examination and was appointed Recorder of the Palace Administration Bureau, then transferred as Instructor at the National Academy, promoted to Doctor of Letters, and appointed Right Remonstrator. Through successive promotions he rose to Counselor-at-Large and Court Diarist, then to Court Academician and Minister of Ceremonial. He entered the Privy Council as Scholar and rose to Minister of Affairs. He was promoted to Commissioner of Imperial Relatives and eventually reached the rank of Grand Councillor and Minister of Personnel. He received the title of Grand Academician of the Pavilion of Refined Culture and was created Duke of Yŏngga. His honorific title was "Duke of Perfect Loyalty and Harmonious Virtue."

    His wife was the daughter of the Eminent Minister Ryu Pyŏnil, created Duchess of Pyon. She bore five sons: Chun, Jongjŏng, Ko, Hu, and Kyŏm—all created dukes. Ko became the Director of Imperial Relatives and Lord of Munhwa; Jongjŏng took the monastic path and became Supreme Administrator of the Two Magistracies, also created Lord of Kwangbok. Four daughters married into the royal house and esteemed families. Thus one household produced nine titled lords, something unheard of in antiquity.

    When the grandfather Master Munching was advanced in years but still vigorous, the Minister served as Examiner of Civil Candidates. When the Minister in turn reached old age and retired as Prime Minister, his son Kilch'ang brought disciples to offer congratulations. Two of the Minister's own disciples and three of their disciples became successive examiners—truly a remarkable legacy.

    The distant ancestor, the Great General Kim Haeng, served with distinction the dynastic founder and was enfeoffed with the Kwŏn surname. Generation after generation preserved his virtue, down to Master Munching. Master Munching, through prayer at the Water Moon Bodhisattva image at the Temple of Blessings, brought the Minister into the world on the eleventh day of the eleventh month of the third year of the Zhongtong era, a time when Heaven's mysterious mechanisms worked in perfect harmony.

    The Minister possessed a temperament gentle as spring breezes and clear as cloudless skies. With reverence he served his sovereign; with sincerity he honored his parents; with harmony he treated his colleagues; with benevolence he regarded his kinsmen. His eye never lingered upon beauty; his mouth never uttered profit. Though his frame grew old, he never ceased his studies and never set down his brush. Though he rose to the highest ranks, he treated the lowliest servants with respect due to the great. Though his verse was spare in word, it cut deep with meaning. The great scholars Mun Jì and Hong Hyŏk constantly praised his work with admiration, yet he took no pride in this. He labored in the inner councils for thirteen years and sat in the seat of Prime Minister for twenty-two years, yet he never grew satisfied. Small wonder that the five blessings crowned his life.

    His epitaph reads:

    *The Kwŏn line flows from Kim's ancient stream,*
    *Its source in fair Kyerim's gentle realm.*
    *Generation unto generation,*
    *Virtue's music echoed through the years.*

    *The father received what was passed down,*
    *Righteousness his abundant store.*
    *Heaven bestowed both honor and long life,*
    *Upon a man of worth supreme.*

    *With public heart forever mindful,*
    *With public action ever true.*
    *Blessings yet unspent shall multiply,*
    *And grace descend on all his line.*

    *Like clouds his progeny gathered,*
    *Each one virtuous, each one kind.*
    *What fortune needs divining now?*
    *What sign could clearer be than this?*
